===Etymology===
{{etyl|ang}} {{term|cald|lang=ang}}, the Anglian form of West Saxon {{term|ceald|ċeald}}, from {{proto|Germanic|kaldoz}}, a participle form of {{proto|Germanic|kal-|cold|title=}}. Cognate with West Frisian {{term|kâd}}, Dutch {{term|koud}}, German {{term|kalt}}, Swedish {{term|kall}}, Danish {{term|kold}}.

===Adjective===
{{en-adj|er}}

# {{context|of a thing}} Having a low [[temperature]].
#: ''A '''cold''' wind whistled through the trees.''
# {{context|of the weather}} Causing the air to be cold.
#: ''The forecast is that it will be very '''cold''' today.''
# {{context|of a person or animal}} Feeling the sensation of [[coldness]], especially to the point of discomfort.
#: ''She was so '''cold''' she was shivering.''
# Unfriendly, emotionally distant or unfeeling.
#: ''She shot me a '''cold''' glance before turning her back.''
# Completely [[unprepared]]; without introduction.
#: ''He was assigned '''cold''' calls for the first three months.''
# Deprived of the metaphorical [[heat]] associated with [[life]] or [[consciousness]]
#: ''I knocked him out '''cold'''.''

